[1
Date: Wed, 20 May 1998 20:34:03 -500
From: Dr. Juan MOREIRA, "CECOMET" <apostol1@ECUA.NET.ec>

I hear from people with large experience in field work in the Andean
communities in Ecuador about cultural practices during funeral activities
and breeding of rodents (guinea pigs).
These persons told me that people in Andean communities used to eat guinea
pigs during funeral activities roasted or cooked with the potato soup. Women
used to prepare the food, but they were not too exposed to blood because the
animals were killed by cervical compression, and afterwards were boiled
before peeling and extraction of organs.
I think that this information makes less probable the hypothesis that [the
recent outbreak was food borne. Airborne is the most plausible form of
transmission in this outbreak, and probably most of the cases were a primary
form of pneumonic plague. But it is also probable that the index case or one
of the [early cases was infected by another mechanism (develop a bubonic
form, after a septicemic form and after a secondary pneumonic form). It is
important to know by which mechanism and to know if there are transmission
of the disease. The confirmation of a continued transmission implies the
risk of another outbreak.
If the prevalence of infected sentinels animals is unknown, case-finding
activities in animals must be implemented. These will be one of the more
useful data to propose control activities.
Other important action to be implemented is case-finding of lymphangitis or
abscess in humans in the region. It seems that lymphangitis was a commonly
complaint in the region a few years ago.
Finally, people from the region also told me that rodent (guinea pigs)
control activities would be culturally unacceptable. Vaccination will be
also unaccepted. People also say that guinea pigs fleas don't bite humans.
For these reasons it is also important to know the following information:
Is there specificity of hosts in guinea pigs fleas?,
What is the flea index in sentinels animals?, and which species?.
Are there _Xenopsylla_? (the plague vector).

--
