[2
Date: Thu, 21 May 1998 17:19:02 -0400
From: FERNANDO DIAS DE AVILA PIRES

It is uncommon to have both pneumonic and bubonic plague occurring at the
same time. An outbreak may begin as bubonic plague, transmitted by fleas from
non-human reservoirs. In cold places a patient may develop pneumonia, and
have the lungs invaded by _Yersinia_. This is known as secondary pneumonic
plague. Then, this patient spreads the bacteria by cough droplets, and
becomes a source of primary pneumonic plague, which is of direct
transmission. Bubonic plague is slow in spreading, contrary to what happens
in pneumonic plague, where a number of people can be infected at the same
time, by a single source, as it seems to have been the present case in
Ecuador. In the Andes of Ecuador and Peru, traditional mourning ceremonies
last several days, with relatives and friends crowding into the deceased's
house.
Only a few species of fleas become "blocked" and are considered to be good
vectors: those found in commensal _Rattus rattus_ (_Xenopsylla chaeopis_,
_X. brasiliensis_) or, in the case of South America, _Polygenis bolshi_,
among a few others. In the literature there is proof of experimental and
occasional mechanical transmission by other fleas, as _Pulex irritans_ and
_P.acari_. As to cuyes being good sentinels, it must be noted that in places
where plague outbreaks occur periodically, cuyes are notably resistant to
plague, and there is no cuye high mortality before the first human cases are
diagnosed.
--
FERNANDO DIAS DE AVILA PIRES
